      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome, and thank you for joining this course on AI in Advertising. Over the next few lessons, we are going to explore something that is genuinely reshaping the world around us. Artificial intelligence is now deeply embedded in how adverts are created, how they are targeted, and how they are personalised, often at a scale that was simply not possible just a few years ago. And while that brings some remarkable opportunities, it also brings some very real risks. We are talking about questions of truth, fairness, and whether some of these techniques cross a line into manipulation. Now, if those words sound a little serious, do not worry. This course is designed to be accessible to everyone, so no prior knowledge is needed whatsoever. Whether you work in marketing, you are just curious about how this all works, or you want to be a more informed consumer, you are in exactly the right place. So let us get started."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "So, let's talk about targeting. When you see an advert online, it hasn't appeared by accident. AI systems are constantly working behind the scenes, deciding who sees which adverts based on things like your age, where you live, and how you behave online. Now, on the surface, that sounds quite useful. Relevant adverts for the right people. But here's where it gets complicated. Those same systems can quietly exclude certain groups from seeing opportunities, whether that's job adverts, financial products, or housing. And often, nobody has deliberately programmed that exclusion. It creeps in through the data the AI has been trained on, data that reflects existing inequalities in society. There's also a real concern around vulnerable people, such as those struggling with debt or mental health challenges, who can end up being specifically targeted in ways that aren't in their best interests. So targeting isn't just a technical process. It carries genuine ethical weight."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So, one of the most powerful things AI brings to advertising is the ability to reach exactly the right people at exactly the right time. Rather than showing an advert to everyone and hoping for the best, AI looks at things like your browsing history, what you've bought before, and even where you are, to figure out who is most likely to be interested in a product. This means advertisers can target specific groups based on age, interests, and online behaviour, which makes their budgets go much further because they're not wasting money showing adverts to people who simply aren't interested. It sounds like a win all round, and in many ways it is. But here's something worth keeping in mind: the system can only work with the data it's given. If that data doesn't reflect everyone equally, then certain groups might be overlooked or unfairly targeted. That's something we'll be exploring as we go through this course."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "Now, this is where things get genuinely uncomfortable. Modern advertising algorithms are extraordinarily good at detecting when you are emotionally vulnerable. If you have been searching for information about bereavement, illness, or financial stress, the system notices. And rather than leaving you alone, advertisers can use that data to serve you targeted ads at precisely the moment you are least equipped to think critically. The people most at risk here are children, who lack the experience to recognise manipulation, and older adults, who may be less familiar with how these systems work. What makes this especially troubling is the concept of personalisation. What sounds like a helpful, tailored experience can actually be a precision tool for exploitation. And technically, you may have agreed to all of this buried somewhere in a lengthy terms and conditions document that nobody actually reads. So informed consent, in any meaningful sense, is rarely happening here."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "Now, one of the most troubling aspects of AI-powered advertising is how it can be used to target people at their most vulnerable moments. Think about someone who has been searching for help with a gambling problem, or a teenager browsing social media late at night. AI systems can identify these patterns and serve highly specific ads that exploit those exact vulnerabilities. We have seen debt consolidation products pushed towards families already struggling financially, and mental health data used to target people in genuine distress. There are also serious concerns about children being exposed to content that simply is not appropriate for them, because the targeting systems are not always as careful as they should be. The real danger here is that AI makes this kind of targeting incredibly precise and scalable. What might have been a limited problem in the past can now reach millions of people almost instantly. That precision, without proper safeguards, can cause very real harm."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "Now, one of the most troubling aspects of AI-driven advertising is who it targets and how. Algorithms are incredibly good at identifying vulnerability. They can recognise patterns that suggest someone is struggling with addiction, going through emotional distress, or is simply a child who doesn't yet have the critical thinking skills to question what they're seeing. Gambling companies, for example, have been caught using these tools to follow vulnerable users around the internet, serving them ads at precisely the moments they're most likely to give in. And all of this is made possible because we've handed over enormous amounts of personal data, often without truly understanding what we've agreed to. Those lengthy terms and conditions? Most people don't read them, and the companies know that. So when we talk about personalisation in advertising, we also need to ask a serious question: at what point does personalisation stop being helpful and start being exploitative? That's the line we need to examine."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "So, what protections actually exist for consumers when it comes to AI-driven advertising? Quite a few, as it turns out. In the UK, legislation like the Online Safety Act and GDPR places real legal limits on how companies can use AI to target and profile you. You also have rights around opting out of personalised ads in many situations, so it is worth knowing those exist. Transparency is a big part of this too. Advertisers are increasingly expected to be upfront when AI has been used to create or tailor content. Beyond that, independent audits can play a really useful role in spotting bias or manipulative patterns in automated systems before they cause harm. And if something does go wrong, there should be clear routes for consumers to raise complaints and seek redress. The message here is that protection is possible, but it relies on strong rules, honest practice, and people knowing their rights."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let us bring everything together from this lesson. The core idea is that AI-powered advertising is not random. It is precise, it is personalised, and it is shaped by data that you may not even realise you have shared. And because the systems behind it are trained on imperfect data, bias can creep in quietly, without anyone deliberately choosing it. Personalisation might feel helpful, but it is never truly neutral. There are always choices being made about what you see and why. And increasingly, the messages themselves are crafted to connect with you emotionally, which is worth being aware of. A useful habit to develop is simply asking yourself who stands to benefit when an advert feels particularly well-timed or persuasive. Finally, I would encourage you to take one practical step before the next lesson. Go into the settings on a platform you use regularly and have a look at what targeting preferences or data permissions are currently switched on. You might be surprised by what you find."
        }
      ]
    }
